{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537988"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16083"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16083"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.53,0.11,0.24,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63878"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8774"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49308"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1325"},{"type":"tags","id":"1975"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29714"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63878"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man is admitted to the rehabilitation ward following decompressive surgery for cauda equina syndrome. Three weeks ago, he sustained a lumbar injury after falling from a ladder. He initially presented with urinary retention, saddle anaesthesia, and bilateral leg weakness. After urgent surgical decompression, he has improving lower limb power but continues to have difficulty initiating micturition and requires intermittent self-catheterisation. He has a history of hypertension and takes amlodipine. He works as a carpenter and lives with his wife.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals reduced sensation in the S2-4 dermatomes, reduced anal tone, and Medical Research Council grade 3/5 power in his lower limbs bilaterally. Post-void bladder scan shows 400 mL residual volume.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following outcomes is most likely for this man 12 months post injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Losing employment","Urinary bladder symptoms","Ongoing saddle parathesia","Sexual dysfunction","Bowel dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cauda equina syndrome following trauma and surgical decompression. Long-term outcomes vary depending on the timing of surgical intervention and the extent of neurological damage, but certain patterns are well-documented in the literature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary bladder symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E are the most likely to persist at 12 months post-injury. Studies show that up to 80% of patients continue to have some degree of bladder dysfunction, including difficulties with initiation of micturition, incomplete emptying, and the need for ongoing intermittent self-catheterisation. This patient\u0027s current high post-void residual volume suggests significant detrusor dysfunction that is likely to persist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELosing employment\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely at 12 months, particularly given his improving lower limb strength. Most patients with cauda equina syndrome can return to modified work duties with appropriate workplace adaptations and rehabilitation support, and self reported studies show the majority of patients who are employed when presenting with cauda equina syndrome, remain employed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOngoing saddle paraesthesia\u003C/strong\u003E, while common initially, tends to improve significantly by 12 months post-injury, especially in cases where early surgical decompression was performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESexual dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E, although a significant concern in cauda equina syndrome, typically shows improvement by 12 months, however remains an ongoing issue in a large number of patients. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBowel dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E generally has a better prognosis than bladder dysfunction, with most patients regaining satisfactory bowel control within 12 months through establishment of effective bowel routines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to optimising outcomes is early recognition and surgical intervention, followed by comprehensive rehabilitation including bladder training, physiotherapy, and occupational therapy. Patient education and engagement in self-management strategies are crucial for long-term success.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early bladder and bowel management is crucial for preventing complications in cauda equina rehabilitation","A structured, multidisciplinary rehabilitation program improves outcomes in cauda equina syndrome","Patient education and engagement in self-management is essential for long-term success in neurogenic bladder dysfunction"],"references":["Woodfield J, Hoeritzauer I, Jamjoom AA, Jung J, Lammy S, Pronin S, Hannan CJ, Watts A, Hughes L, Moon RD, Darwish S. Presentation, management, and outcomes of cauda equina syndrome up to one year after surgery, using clinician and participant reporting: A multi-centre prospective cohort study. The Lancet Regional Health\u2013Europe. 2023 Jan 1;24. Available online at ; https://www.thelancet.com/pdfs/journals/lanepe/PIIS2666-7762(22)00241-1.pdf","Hazelwood JE, Hoeritzauer I, Pronin S, Demetriades AK. An assessment of patient-reported long-term outcomes following surgery for cauda equina syndrome. Acta Neurochirurgica. 2019 Sep 1;161:1887-94. Available online at ; https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007/s00701-019-03973-7.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49308"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16083"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49308"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T18:44:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T18:45:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8774"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63878"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type